    id: 'fc-c2-2-9-02',
    topicId: 'topic-c2-2-9',
    front: 'Why does software overwriting fail for SSDs, and what method should be used instead?',
    back: 'SSDs use wear leveling — the SSD controller distributes writes evenly across flash cells to prevent any single cell from wearing out prematurely. When you issue an overwrite command, the controller writes to fresh cells and marks the old ones for future use. The original data remains in those old cells, unreachable by the OS but still physically present.\n\nThis means overwriting commands (including 7-pass DoD wiping) cannot guarantee all data is erased on an SSD.\n\nCorrect methods for SSDs:\n• ATA Secure Erase: built-in drive command that tells the controller to reset ALL cells (including spares) to factory state\n• Cryptographic wipe: if the drive was encrypted, destroy the key — the ciphertext becomes permanently unreadable\n• Physical destruction: shredding, drilling, or incineration',
