    front: 'What is degaussing, what media types does it work on, and what is a critical side effect?',
    back: 'Degaussing uses an extremely powerful magnetic field to randomize the magnetic domains on storage media, permanently destroying the data.\n\nEffective on: HDDs, magnetic tape (LTO, DLT), floppy disks — any magnetic storage media.\n\nNOT effective on: SSDs, NVMe drives, USB flash drives, SD cards, optical media (CD/DVD/Blu-ray). These store data electronically, not magnetically — there are no magnetic domains to disrupt.\n\nCritical side effect: degaussing permanently destroys the HDD servo tracks used by the drive controller to position the read/write head. A degaussed HDD cannot be reformatted, repartitioned, or reused in any way — it is physically destroyed as a functional drive. This is a frequently tested exam point.',
