    topicId: 'topic-c2-2-9',
    front: 'What is a cryptographic wipe (crypto erase) and what is the key requirement for it to work?',
    back: 'Cryptographic wipe destroys data by deleting or destroying the encryption key that protects it. The encrypted data remains physically on the drive, but without the key, it is mathematically unrecoverable — indistinguishable from random noise.\n\nSpeed: nearly instantaneous — no need to overwrite every sector.\n\nKey requirement: the drive MUST have been encrypted BEFORE the data was written. You cannot retroactively encrypt plaintext data and call it erased — the plaintext already exists on the drive sectors and must be physically overwritten.\n\nUse cases: BitLocker (delete key protectors), Self-Encrypting Drives (SED crypto erase command), iOS/Android factory reset (destroys the hardware-bound encryption key), cloud storage (delete the KMS key).',
