    back: 'Clear: overwrites data using standard read/write operations. Protects against casual or non-laboratory recovery. Example: single or multi-pass software overwrite. Appropriate for lower-sensitivity scenarios where data will not be subjected to forensic analysis.\n\nPurge: applies more advanced techniques resistant to laboratory attack. Examples: ATA Secure Erase, degaussing, cryptographic erase. Appropriate for sensitive data.\n\nDestroy: physical destruction so the media cannot be reused. Examples: shredding, incineration, disintegration. Absolute — provides the highest assurance. Required for classified/top-secret data.\n\nMemory tip: Clear → Purge → Destroy increases in both assurance and irreversibility.',
