    front: 'Compare WEP, WPA2-AES, and WPA3 wireless encryption standards.',
    back: 'WEP (Wired Equivalent Privacy): broken — uses RC4 cipher with fundamental design flaws. Cracked in minutes with freely available tools. Deprecated in 2004. Never use.\n\nWPA2-AES (CCMP): uses AES encryption — still strong. Most widely deployed standard. Vulnerable to offline dictionary attacks if the pre-shared key (PSK) handshake is captured.\n\nWPA3: uses SAE (Simultaneous Authentication of Equals) instead of PSK handshake. Key advantage: even if an attacker captures the SAE handshake, it cannot be cracked offline — each authentication attempt requires online interaction. Also provides forward secrecy. Best option when available.\n\nAlways choose AES (CCMP) over TKIP when configuring WPA2 — TKIP has known vulnerabilities and is deprecated.',
