    front: 'What is the WPS vulnerability and how is it exploited?',
    back: 'WPS (Wi-Fi Protected Setup) was designed for easy device pairing using an 8-digit PIN. It has a fundamental design flaw: the PIN is validated in two halves (first 4 digits, then last 4 digits) separately — reducing attack combinations from 100,000,000 to just 11,000.\n\nExploit: tools like Reaver brute-force the WPS PIN in under 24 hours. Once the PIN is cracked, the tool retrieves the full WPA2 passphrase automatically — bypassing even a strong 20-character passphrase entirely.\n\nFix: disable WPS completely. There is no patch — the flaw is in the design of the protocol. Verify it is actually disabled; some routers require a reboot and may re-enable WPS after firmware updates.',
