    front: 'Does hiding the SSID provide meaningful wireless security? Why or why not?',
    back: 'No. SSID hiding is security through obscurity — it provides a minor inconvenience, not real protection.\n\nWhy it fails: even when a network does not broadcast its SSID, it can be discovered using passive Wi-Fi scanning tools that detect probe requests. When a client device that previously connected to the hidden network roams away and searches for it, it broadcasts the SSID in probe requests — revealing the name to any attacker with a Wi-Fi scanner.\n\nAdditionally, hidden SSIDs cause connectivity issues for legitimate users.\n\nBest practice: keep SSID broadcast enabled and rely on WPA3 with a strong passphrase for actual security. Changing the SSID from the default router-brand name (which reveals the device model) is a worthwhile step.',
