    topicId: 'topic-c2-2-10',
    front: 'What is UPnP, why should it be disabled on SOHO routers, and what is the DMZ?',
    back: 'UPnP (Universal Plug and Play): allows devices on the network to automatically create port forwarding rules on the router without manual configuration. Convenient for gaming consoles and media devices — but malware can also abuse UPnP to open inbound ports, creating a backdoor the attacker controls. Disable UPnP unless a specific application requires it.\n\nDMZ (Demilitarized Zone): places a single device outside the router\'s firewall — all unsolicited inbound ports and protocols are forwarded to it. The device is fully exposed to internet traffic.\n\nDMZ use case: game consoles (to avoid NAT issues), or web/mail servers requiring unrestricted inbound connections. Risk: a compromised DMZ device gives the attacker a foothold inside the network. Prefer specific port forwarding rules over full DMZ exposure when possible.',
