    front: 'What is MAC address filtering and why is it considered a weak security control?',
    back: 'MAC address filtering creates an allowlist of hardware (MAC) addresses permitted to associate with the wireless network. The router rejects connection attempts from MACs not on the list.\n\nWhy it is weak: MAC addresses can be trivially spoofed on any operating system in seconds. An attacker:\n1. Passively monitors the network with a Wi-Fi adapter in monitor mode\n2. Captures the MAC address of a legitimate connected device from its traffic\n3. Sets their own adapter\'s MAC to match the legitimate device\'s MAC\n4. Connects to the network\n\nMAC filtering adds minor friction (a small additional step for the attacker) but provides no meaningful security against any determined attacker. It does not substitute for strong WPA3 encryption and a strong passphrase.',
