    front: 'How do you distinguish a real security alert from a fake scareware alert on a Windows PC?',
    back: 'Real security alert:\n• Comes from installed security software (Windows Defender, Norton, etc.)\n• Appears as a Windows notification or within the AV application\'s own window\n• Does NOT ask you to call a phone number\n• Does NOT ask for payment to remove a threat\n• Provides specific file path and threat name\n• Can be verified by opening the AV application directly\n\nFake alert / scareware:\n• Appears in a web browser as a pop-up or full-screen page\n• Claims to be from Microsoft, Apple, or a well-known AV brand\n• Provides a phone number to call immediately\n• Creates urgency: "Your data is being stolen RIGHT NOW"\n• May lock the browser in full-screen (press F11 or Escape to exit)\n• Has no actual access to your system — it is just a webpage\n\nResponse to fake alert: press Escape/F11 → close the tab → if tab resists closing, use Task Manager to kill the browser process → clear cache and cookies → run a real scan to confirm no infection.',
