    id: 'fc-c2-3-4-07',
    topicId: 'topic-c2-3-4',
    front: 'What causes widespread certificate errors across multiple HTTPS sites on a Windows PC?',
    back: 'If a user reports that multiple HTTPS sites suddenly show certificate errors simultaneously (not just one site), the most common cause is an incorrect system clock.\n\nTLS certificate validation requires the client\'s clock to fall within the certificate\'s validity period. If the system clock drifts significantly — which can happen with a dead CMOS battery — all certificates appear expired or not-yet-valid depending on how far the clock has drifted.\n\nFix: correct the system date and time. All certificate errors will resolve instantly.\n\nOther causes of certificate errors (site-specific, not widespread):\n• Expired server certificate — site owner must renew\n• Self-signed certificate — install organization\'s root CA cert via certmgr.msc or GPO\n• Hostname mismatch — possible MitM or server misconfiguration; do not proceed\n• Revoked certificate — avoid the site',
    difficulty: 2,
    tags: null,
